article.description: David  Robinson, who had 13 points and nine rebounds, passed 20,000 career points in leading the Spurs to a 109-88 win over the Golden State Warriors on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Admiral surpasses 20,000-point milestone
article.linkText: Robinson passes 20,000 mark, Spurs rip Warriors
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- David Robinson hit another milestone and the San Antonio Spurs got another much-needed victory. Robinson, who had 13 points and nine rebounds, passed 20,000 career points in leading the Spurs to a 109-88 win over the Golden State Warriors on Tuesday night. The 7-foot center, the 27th NBA player to surpass that point total, now has 20,001 points. He passed the mark by hitting two free throws to a standing ovation in the third quarter. "He's special to this city, not just for the points," said Spurs coach Gregg Popovich. "Everybody is thrilled for him, as I am and the team is. "That's another element of what makes him a wonderful human being to this city." Even the low-key Robinson, 36, was impressed with his point total. "That's a pretty good milesetone, one that will be around for a while," he said. He was upset about a missed dunk just before the free throws. "I was a little frustrated when I missed the dunk and missed another little shot," he said. "I am glad to get that one over with and we can move on." Duncan had 15 of his 23 points in the first half, along with seven rebounds, as he led three other Spurs in double figures. Steve Smith had 16 points, Malik Rose 13 and Bruce Bowen 11. With the Spurs' third straight win, they are 39-21, third in the Midwest Division. "We're building momentum and this was a great one at home to continue it with," Duncan said. The Spurs also extended their win streak against the Warriors to 16. The Warriors' last win was March 3, 1998. Antawn Jamison, who was 11-of-18 from the field, led Golden State with 24 points and 10 rebounds. Larry Hughes also had 20 and Danny Fortson scored 13. The Warriors outrebounded the Spurs 48-46, but could not close the gap, shooting 40 from the field. They were hampered by 18 turnovers that the Spurs converted into 18 points. "Turnovers were the key," said Jamison. "I thought we played them fairly well and our intensity was there. There were just too many turnovers that they capitalized on and turned into points." Golden State started the third quarter hitting its first six points and cutting the lead to 11, but that would be the closest it got. When Danny Ferry hit a 3-pointer at 6:33 of the fourth quarter, it extended their biggest lead of the game to 25. The Spurs trailed early 19-13, then went on a 19-3 run that ended at 10:53 in the second quarter. They went into halftime with a 57-42 edge. "I think they got up on us before the half and we lost a little bit of heart," said Fortston, the Warriors' leading rebounder. "After that we didn't match their intensity, and when you don't play hard against a team like the Spurs, you get your butt kicked. And that's what happened: We got our butts kicked." Game notes
San Antonio had a season high with 31 assists. ... The Warriors are 2-30 when trailing at halftime, worst in the league. ... The Warriors' Jason Richardson did not play for the second straight game, sitting out with a left ankle sprain. The rookie guard has averaged 19.8 points since the All-Star break.
